How to store spinach (or badically any green) so that it lasts longer.
Just place in a container with a clean, dry paper towel. Close container up and flip upside. Store in fridge upside down. 

the towel will absorb the moisture in the container that will cause your leafy green to spoil before you get around to eating them!

✨Chocolate Beet Muffins ✨ Moist, chocolatey and, yep, loaded with beets…in a rather tasty way, if I do say so myself. 🙂

I recently had someone tell me that recipes like these Chocolate Beet Muffins feel deceptive because the veggies aren’t obvious.
To which I said “It is only deceptive if you don’t tell someone veggies are in them.  What if it is just a delicious and different way to eat a known veggie?”

You see, for me, veggie-loading isn’t about tricking people, it is about helping people have positive experience with vegetables in whatever way feels good for them so that they want to keep eating veggies later on. And maybe in more obvious ways!

 And this is true me for me and my family. We don’t love beets but we sure do enjoy them in these muffins…and we know they are in there!

 And that’s all I want for you with veggie-loaded recipes. To help you eat veggies in a way you love in food that you love.

✨Pink Beet Pancakes✨Oat based, naturally sweetened, and turned a beautiful bright pink by the addition of cooked beets, these pink pancakes are sure dazzle all that come to your breakfast table.

A few tips for success:
💖 I find ROASTED beets give these pancakes the most vibrant color. Beets prepared with other methods will give at turn the pancakes pink…just lighter in color since they have lost some of their juices during cooking. 
💖Cooking these pancakes low and slow will help them to be pink on the outside as well as the inside! Too hot of a pan and with too much oil will brown them on the outside…though they will still be a beautiful pink on the inside.
💖Make them ahead and store them in your fridge or freezer for a quick #veggieloaded breakfast any day of the week!

✨Greek Yogurt Ranch Dip✨ It is silly easy to make and just makes raw veggies ….so good.

You might not know this, but before I was a full time food blogger….I was a full time teacher. For many years.

And I learned a lot during that time, but one thing that I absolutely learned is that one of THE BEST ways to help a kiddo eat a veggie is to add a really tasty dip.

Really. Add a good dip and the veggies will likely get eaten. I tested this theory many times during my years in the classroom and it was a success more often than not. So, in case you need this hack in your life…I feel obligated to share.

And while there is nothing wrong with a store bought ranch, I personally love this version because it is so easy to make with things I often have on hand. Just whisk a little dill, lemon, salt and garlic powder into some Greek yogurt and you have the perfect protein rich dip that also might help your kids (or you) get some extra veggies in.

Find the recipe by clicking the link in my bio or searching “ranch dip” on thenaturalnurturer.com. #veggieloaded #eatmorevggies

I always get asked about how to make veggie-loaded oatmeal and here it is! 

Single serving
- 1/2 cup rolled oats
- 1/2 cup water or milk of choice
- 1/4 cup grated carrot, zucchini, or yellow squash (I like to grate them ahead of time and store in the fridge for to make mornings extra easy.
- 1 whisked eggs or 3 Tablespoons egg whites
-top with fruit, peanut butter, and maple syrup/honey

Stir together oats, water/milk, and grated veggies in a microwave safe bowl. Microwave for about 1 minute. The grated veggies are nice and small and will cook fast with the oats.

Stir in eggs/egg whites and return to the microwave for about 60-90 seconds or until the liquid has been absorbed and eggs cooked. 

Top with fruit, nut butter and maple syrup/honey and enjoy!

I do have a stovetop version I like to make on morning when I have more time. Adding the eggs to that version takes a bit more finesse, so be sure to check out my tips in the recipe. You can find that by searching “carrot protein oatmeal” on thenaturalnurturer.com.

 -olive oil

-1 large egg white or you can just add another egg
-salt and pepper to taste
-cheese or fresh herbs to top
Instructions 
Heat a medium or large skillet over medium heat. Once hot, add the oil and let that heat up for 30 seconds.

Add the riced cauliflower to the hot skillet. Use a spatula to spread the cauliflower out in an even layer and cook until tender and golden, 3 to 4 minutes, stirring the cauliflower once or twice.

In a small bowl, whisk eggs, egg white, and salt and pepper.

Pour egg mixture into the hot skillet with the riced cauliflower and cook and stir just until eggs are cooked.
Top with cheese (if using) while hot and let it melt a bit for about 30 seconds, if using.
Enjoy warm with a side of toast, fruit or in a breakfast wrap.

✨3 Ways To Cook A Butternut Squash WHOLE✨
I think we have all avoided adding a butternut squash to a meal simply because they are a pain to cut when raw. Luckily, they are easy to cut, deseed and peel when cooked…and you can do it whole! Here my 3 ways….

To Roast:
Wash your squash and use a sharp knife to puncture it about 8-10 times. Place it in a baking pan and cook in a 425℉ oven and roast for 60-80 minutes (if using a bigger squash, it will take longer). Your squash is done when a fork or knife and easily go into the flesh. Let squash cool a bit before handling.

Instant Pot:
Wash your squash and use a sharp knife to puncture it about 8-10 times. Pour 1 cup of water into your pressure cooked and place your squash in the IP. It is important that your squash fit ALL THE WAY in your pressure cooker for this method. Secure the lid and turn pressure release knob to a sealed position. Cook at high pressure for 25 minutes. If you are using a large squash, cut in half to help it cook or add more cooking time. When cook time is complete, use a natural release for 10 minutes and then carefully release the remaining pressure. Let squash cool a bit before handling.

Slow Cooker:
Wash your squash and use a sharp knife to puncture it about 8-10 times. Pour 1 cup of water into your slow cooker.Cook 4-5 hours on high or 6-8 hours on low. You will know your squash is done when it can easily be pierced with a fork or knife.Let squash cool a bit before handling.

To which I said “It is only deceptive if you don’t tell someone veggies are in them.  What if it is just a delicious and different way to eat a known veggie?”

You see, for me, veggie-loading isn’t about tricking people, it is about helping people have positive experience with vegetables in whatever way feels good for them so that they want to keep eating veggies later on. And maybe in more obvious ways!

 And this is true me for me and my family. We don’t love beets but we sure do enjoy them in these muffins…and we know they are in there!
